te_media/pressroom/documents/2011/Apr/06/IAE_Energy_Report_Web2_05.04.2011.pdf Energy Policy and Economic Recovery 2010-2015] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130514085614/http://www.iae.ie/site_media/pressroom/documents/2011/Apr/06/IAE_Energy_Report_Web2_05.04.2011.pdf |date=14 May 2013 }}, page 5. ''Irish Academy of Engineering'', 2011. [https://web.archive.org/web/20130514085614/http://www.iae.ie/site_media/pressroom/documents/2011/Apr/06/IAE_Energy_Report_Web2_05.04.2011.pdf Archive]</ref> By contrast, the [[Sustainable Energy Authority of Ireland]] says wind power costs the same as gas power.<ref>[http://www.irishexaminer.com/ireland/special-report-a-look-at-the-wind-energy-debate-264502.html SPECIAL REPORT: A look at the wind energy debate Monday, 7 April 2014, By Claire O'Sullivan ''Irish Examiner''] [http://arquivo.pt/wayback/20160515180904/http://www.irishexaminer.com/ireland/special%2Dreport%2Da%2Dlook%2Dat%2Dthe%2Dwind%2Denergy%2Ddebate%2D264502.html Archive]</ref>\n\n===Peat and {{CO2}} impacts===\nAccess roads on top of peatlands results in the drainage and then eventual [[oxidation]] of some of the peat. The turbines represent a minor impact,<ref name=Lindsay2010>Richard Lindsay. [https://web.archive.org/web/20110703112406/http://www.uel.ac.uk/erg/documents/Peatbogsandcarbon-14thJune2010-PDF300dpi.pdf Peat bogs and carbon], page 164. ''[[University of East London]]'', 14 June 2010</ref> provided that the entire wind farm area is not drained, potentially emitting more CO2 than the turbines would save.<ref name=\"uel.ac.uk\">Richard Lindsay. [https://web.archive.org/web/20131218090914/http://www.uel.ac.uk/erg/documents/Derrybrien.pdf Wind farms and blanket peat], page 70, 79-87, 111. ''[[University of East London]]'', 2004</ref> Biochemist Mike Hall stated in 2009; \"wind farms (built on peat bogs) may eventually emit more carbon than an equivalent [[coal-fired power station]]\" if drained.<ref>{{cite news|author=Fred Pearce |url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2009/aug/13/wind-farm-peat-bog |title=Greenwash: How a wind farm could emit more carbon than a coal power station &#124; Fred Pearce &#124; Environment |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date= |accessdate=2017-01-15}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2014 report for the Northern Ireland Environment Agency, which has similar peatland, it notes that siting wind turbines on [[peatland]] could release considerable carbon dioxide from the peat, and also damage the peatland contributions to [[flood control]] and water quality: \"The potential knock-on effects of using the peatland resource for wind turbines are considerable and it is arguable that the impacts on this facet of [[biodiversity]] will have the most noticeable and greatest financial implications for Northern Ireland.\"<ref>David Tosh, W. Ian Montgomery & Neil Reid [http://www.doeni.gov.uk/niea/a_review_of_the_impacts_of_onshore_wind_energy_for_publication_9.12.14.pdf A review of the impacts of onshore wind energy development on biodiversity] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150531205832/http://www.doeni.gov.uk/niea/a_review_of_the_impacts_of_onshore_wind_energy_for_publication_9.12.14.pdf |date=31 May 2015 }}, Northern Ireland Environment Agency, Research and Development Series 14/02, 2014, p.54</ref>\n\nThe [[Irish Peatland Conservation Council]] maintains a database on incidences were turbine construction and their associated works, such as road construction on deep [[peat]], resulted in environmentally degrading \"bog bursts\"/\"peat flows\". Events that accelerate the release of [[carbon dioxide]] into the atmosphere.<ref name=\"IPCC\"/> Following the Corrie Mountain burst of 2008, Ireland was fined by a European Court over its mishandling of wind farms on [[peatland]].<ref name=\"IPCC\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.friendsoftheirishenvironment.org/attachments/article/16473/bog_slides_minister_3.10.08__and_12.05.09.pdf |title=Re: Moratorium on upland wind farm construction |website=Friendsoftheiririshenvironment.org |accessdate=2017-01-15}}</ref>\n\nThe body representing industrial Peat harvesting in Ireland, [[Bord na M\u00f3na]], announced in 2015 the \"biggest change of land use in modern Irish history\": harvesting energy peat is being phased out by 2030, due to the long expected depletion of the profitable lowland peat<ref>{{cite news|author=Joanne Edgar |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/06/14/travel/in-the-bogs-of-western-ireland.html |title=In The Bogs Of Western Ireland |location=Ireland, Republic Of |website=NYTimes.com |date=1987-06-14 |accessdate=2017-01-15}}</ref> at which point the company would complete its transition to becoming a \"sustainable biomass, wind and solar power\" organization.<ref>{{cite web|last1=de R\u00f3iste|first1=Daith\u00ed |title=Bord na M\u00f3na announces biggest change of land use in modern Irish history|url= http://www.bordnamona.ie/news/latest/bord-na-mona-announces-biggest-change-of-land-use-in-modern-irish-history/ |website=Bord na M\u00f3na|publisher=Bord na M\u00f3na|accessdate=6 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Land slides===\n{{main|2003 Derrybrien landslide}}\nIn [[Derrybrien]] County [[Galway]], at the site of what would become Ireland's largest wind farm in 2006, the 70 tower ''Derrybrien'' project, construction disrupted the underlying [[peatland]]. On 16 October 2003, it caused the [[2003 Derrybrien landslide]] which culminated in an almost 2.5&nbsp;km long, 450,000 m<sup>3</sup> peat slide, polluting a nearby lake and killing 50,000 fish.<ref name=\"newscientist.com\">{{cite magazine|last=Douglas |first=Ed |url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/mg19125591.600 |title=The hidden cost of wind turbines |magazine=[[New Scientist]] |date=2006-07-05 |accessdate=2017-01-15}}</ref> If all carbon in the slide is being released, it represents 7\u201315 months of production from the wind farm in avoided carbon dioxide from fossil power.<ref name=\"uel.ac.uk\"/> In 2004, engineering companies were convicted of being responsible for the pollution,<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2004/1020/55807-derrybrien/ |title=Companies convicted for Galway river pollution |journal=RT\u00c9.ie |date=2004-10-20 |accessdate=2017-01-15}}</ref> while the wind farm company was acquitted.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2004/1019/55728-derrybrien/ |title=Galway court dismisses pollution prosecution |journal=RT\u00c9.ie |date=2004-10-19 |accessdate=2017-01-15}}</ref> The Irish government was convicted in 2008 of poor oversight.<ref name=rte2008>{{cite journal|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2008/0703/105303-derrybrien/ |title=EU court rules against Ireland on Derrybrien |journal=RT\u00c9.ie |date=2008-07-03 |accessdate=2017-01-15}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Irish Peatland Conservation Council]] maintains a database on incidences where turbine construction and their associated works, such as road construction on deep [[peat]], resulted in environmentally degrading \"bog bursts\"/\"peat flows\". Events that accelerate the release of [[carbon dioxide]] into the atmosphere.<ref name=\"IPCC\">{{cite web |url= http://www.ipcc.ie/a-to-z-peatlands/peatland-action-plan/habitat-loss-of-peatlands |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140301114417/http://www.ipcc.ie/a-to-z-peatlands/peatland-action-plan/habitat-loss-of-peatlands |url-status= dead |archive-date= 2014-03-01 |title=Habitat Loss of Peatlands, Wind Farms on Peatlands |publisher=[[Irish Peatland Conservation Council]] }}</ref> Following the Corrie Mountain burst of 2008, Ireland was fined by a European Court over its mishandling of wind farms on [[peatland]].<ref name=\"IPCC\"/><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.friendsoftheirishenvironment.org/attachments/article/16473/bog_slides_minister_3.10.08__and_12.05.09.pdf |title=Re: Moratorium on upland wind farm construction |publisher=Friends of the Irish Environment |date=12 May 2009 }}</ref> By 2010, at least three wind farm related peat slides had occurred in Ireland.<ref name=\"Lindsay2010\"/>\n\n==Environmental Impact & Greenhouse gases==\n{{See also|Environmental impact of wind power}}\n[[File:Greenhouse emissions by electricity source.PNG|thumb|upright=1.5|right|Studies by the [[Vattenfall]] electricity company found; electricity generation by [[Hydroelectric]], nuclear stations and wind turbines in-isolation, to all have a far smaller embodied [[carbon footprint]] than other sources represented. These studies on the [[Life-cycle greenhouse-gas emissions of energy sources|total life-cycle, greenhouse gas emissions, per unit of energy generated]] take into account the [[Nordic countries|Nordic]] utilities [[cradle-to-grave]] construction emissions etc. These results are largely in-line with those made in 2014 by the [[Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change]].<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20130627074517/http://srren.ipcc-wg3.de/report/IPCC_SRREN_Annex_II.pdf ]</ref> However they do not assess real-world integrated grid findings and the actual pollution emitted from the addition of wind energy into an electric grid.<ref name=\"wiley1\">{{cite journal |title=Life Cycle Greenhouse Gas Emissions of Utility-Scale Wind Power Systematic Review and Harmonization |author1=Stacey L. Dolan|author2=Garvin A. Heath|doi=10.1111/j.1530-9290.2012.00464.x |volume=16 |journal=Journal of Industrial Ecology |pages=S136\u2013S154|year = 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"sciencedirect.com\">{{cite journal|title=Quantifying CO2 savings from wind power|author=Joseph Wheatley|journal=Energy Policy |volume=63|date=December 2013|pages=89\u201396|doi=10.1016/j.enpol.2013.07.123}}</ref><ref name=\"joewheatley1\">{{cite web|last=Martin |first=Owen |url= http://joewheatley.net/how-much-co2-does-wind-power-save/ |title=Quantifying CO2 savings from wind power &#124; Biospherica |website=Joewheatley.net |date= |accessdate=2017-01-15}}</ref>]]\n\nIn a typical study of a wind farms [[Life cycle assessment]] (LCA), in isolation, it usually results in similar findings as the following 2006 analysis of 3 installations in the US Midwest, were the carbon dioxide ([[CO2]]) emissions of wind power ranged from 14 to 33 [[metric ton]] per GWh (14 - 33 [[gram|g]]{{CO2}}/[[kWh]]) of energy produced, with most of the {{CO2}} emissions coming from the production of concrete for wind-turbine foundations.<ref name=\"White\">{{Cite journal | last1 = White | first1 = S. W. | title = Net Energy Payback and CO2 Emissions from Three Midwestern Wind Farms: An Update | doi = 10.1007/s11053-007-9024-y | journal = Natural Resources Research | volume = 15 | issue = 4 | pages = 271\u2013281 | year = 2007 | pmid =  | pmc = }}</ref>\n\nHowever, when approached from the effects on the grid as a whole, that assess wind turbines' ability to reduce a country's total electric grid [[emission intensity]], a study by the [[Eirgrid|Irish national grid]], a [[List of power stations in the Republic of Ireland|grid that is predominately (~70%) powered by fossil gas]], (and if it was 100% gas, would result in  emissions of 410 - 650 [[gram|g]]{{CO2}}/[[kWh]].<ref name=\"IPCC 2014 Annex III\">{{cite web|title=IPCC Working Group III \u2013 Mitigation of Climate Change, Annex II I: Technology - specific cost and performance parameters |url=http://report.mitigation2014.org/report/ipcc_wg3_ar5_annex-iii.pdf |publisher=IPCC |accessdate=1 August 2014 |page=10 |year=2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141215013236/http://report.mitigation2014.org/report/ipcc_wg3_ar5_annex-iii.pdf |archivedate=15 December 2014 }}</ref><ref name=\"report.mitigation2014.org\">{{cite web|title=IPCC Working Group III \u2013 Mitigation of Climate Change, Annex II Metrics and Methodology. pg 37 to 40,41 |url=http://report.mitigation2014.org/report/ipcc_wg3_ar5_annex-ii.pdf |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150908235241/http://report.mitigation2014.org/report/ipcc_wg3_ar5_annex-ii.pdf |archivedate= 8 September 2015 }}</ref>) found that although \"Producing electricity from wind reduces the consumption of fossil fuels and therefore leads to [electric grid] emissions savings\", with findings in reductions of the grid-wide {{CO2}} emissions to 0.33-0.59 [[metric ton]] of {{CO2}} per MWh (330 - 590 [[gram|g]]{{CO2}}/[[kWh]]).<ref name=\"eirgrid\">{{cite web\n  | url= http://www.eirgrid.com/EirGridPortal/uploads/Publications/Wind%20Impact%20Study%20-%20main%20report.pdf\n  | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20050517213644/http://www.eirgrid.com/EirGridPortal/uploads/Publications/Wind%20Impact%20Study%20-%20main%20report.pdf\n  | url-status= dead\n  | archive-date= 2005-05-17\n  | title= Impact of Wind Generation in Ireland on the Operation of Conventional Plant and the Economic Implications\n  | date=February 2004\n  | publisher= ESB National Grid\n  | accessdate= 2008-01-15 }}</ref>\n\nThese findings were of relatively \"low [emission] savings\", as presented in the Journal of ''[[Energy Policy (journal)|Energy Policy]]'', and were largely due to an over-reliance on the results from the analysis of wind farms LCAs in isolation.<ref name=\"sciencedirect.com\"/><ref name=\"joewheatley1\"/> As high [[electric grid]] penetration by [[intermittent power sources]] e.g. wind power, sources which have low [[capacity factor]]s due to the weather, either requires the [[east\u2013West Interconnector|construction of transmission to neighbouring areas]], [[list of energy storage projects|energy storage projects]] like the 292 MW [[Turlough Hill Power Station]], that have their own additional [[emission intensity]] which must be accounted for,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.seai.ie/uploadedfiles/FundedProgrammes/REHC03001FinalReport.pdf |title=Study of Electricity Storage Technologies and Their Potential to Address Wind Energy Intermittency in Ireland. Co-authored with Dr. Brian \u00d3 Gallach\u00f3ir}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://keith.seas.harvard.edu/papers/164.Safaei.Keith.CompressedAirEnergyStor.p.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-07-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150722005619/http://keith.seas.harvard.edu/papers/164.Safaei.Keith.CompressedAirEnergyStor.p.pdf |archivedate=22 July 2015 }}</ref> or the more common practice of requiring a higher reliance on fossil fuels than the [[spinning reserve]] requirements necessary to back-up the more dependable/[[baseload power]] sources, such as hydropower and [[nuclear power|nuclear energy]].<ref name=\"sciencedirect.com\"/>\n\nThis higher dependence on back-up/[[Load following power plant]]s to ensure a steady [[power grid]] output has the knock-on-effect of more frequent inefficient (in {{CO2}}e g/kW\u00b7h) [[throttle|throttling]] up and down of these other power sources in the grid to accommodate the intermittent power source's variable output. When one includes the intermittent sources total effect it has on other power sources in the grid system, that is, including these inefficient start up emissions of backup power sources to cater for wind energy, into wind energy's total system wide life cycle, this results in a higher real-world emission intensity related to wind energy than the in-isolation ''g/kW\u00b7h'' value, a statistic that is determined by looking at the power source in isolation and thus ignores all down-stream detrimental/inefficiency effects it has on the grid.<ref name=\"sciencedirect.com\"/> In a 2012 paper that appeared in the ''Journal of Industrial Ecology'' it states.<ref name=\"wiley1\"/>\n\n{{Quote|The [[thermal efficiency]] of fossil-based power plants is reduced when operated at fluctuating and suboptimal loads to supplement wind power, which may degrade, to a certain extent, the GHG ([[Greenhouse gas]]) benefits resulting from the addition of wind to the grid. A study conducted by Pehnt and colleagues (2008) reports that a moderate level of [grid] wind penetration (12%) would result in efficiency penalties of 3% to 8%, depending on the type of conventional power plant considered. Gross and colleagues (2006) report similar results, with efficiency penalties ranging from nearly 0% to 7% for up to 20% [of grid] wind penetration. Pehnt and colleagues (2008) conclude that the results of adding offshore wind power in Germany on the background power systems maintaining a level supply to the grid and providing enough reserve capacity amount to adding between 20 and 80 g CO2-eq/kWh to the life cycle GHG emissions profile of wind power.}}\n[[File:AntiWindFarmRochfortbridge.jpg|thumb|Anti Wind Farm poster in [[Rochfortbridge]], County Westmeath in 2014]]\nAccording to the [[IPCC]], wind turbines when assessed in isolation, have a [[median]] life cycle emission value of between 12 and 11 ([[gram|g]]{{CO2}}[[Carbon dioxide equivalent|eq]]/[[kWh]]). While the more dependable alpine Hydropower and nuclear stations have median total life cycle emission values of 24 and 12 g CO2-eq/kWh respectively.<ref name=\"IPCC 2014 Annex III\"/><ref name=\"report.mitigation2014.org\"/>\n\nRegarding interconnections, Ireland is connected to adjacent [[National Grid (Great Britain)|UK National Grid]] at an [[Synchronous grid of Continental Europe#List of electricity interconnection level|electricity interconnection level]] (transmission capacity relative to production capacity) of 9%.<ref name=eil>COM/2015/082 final: \"Achieving the 10% electricity interconnection target\" [http://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/?uri=COM:2015:0082:FIN Text] [http://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/PDF/?uri=CELEX:52015DC0082&from=EN PDF] page 2-5. ''[[European Commission]]'', 25 February 2015. [https://web.archive.org/web/20151225022701/http://ec.europa.eu/priorities/energy-union/docs/interconnectors_en.pdf Archive] [https://www.eumonitor.eu/9353000/1/j4nvhdfdk3hydzq_j9vvik7m1c3gyxp/vjs4eawsiryh Mirror]</ref><!--some upgrades since then--> The two grids have a high wind [[Correlation and dependence|correlation]] of 0.61, whereas the wind [[Correlation coefficient|correlation]] between the Irish grid and the Danish grid is low at 0.09.<ref>Bach, Paul F. \"[http://www.pfbach.dk/firma_pfb/enlarged_wind_power_statistics_2010.pdf Enlarged Wind Power Statistics 2010]\", page 4. [https://web.archive.org/web/20150608064603/http://pfbach.dk/firma_pfb/enlarged_wind_power_statistics_2010.pdf Archive]</ref>\n\n===Tourism===\nOne major aspect of wind farms in Ireland is tourist attraction and also local attraction. The Bord na Mona wind farm in Mount Lucas, Daingean, Co.Offaly has provided a local walk way through the newly established wind farm that attracts people of all ages. The walk way provides a safe environment off-road for walking, running and cycling. The walk way is approximately nine kilometres in distance with numerous stop off points for breaks. Maps can also be located in a variety of locations on the walk for guidance around the wind farm and back to allocated car parks. The walk way also provides aesthetic scenery on a relatively flat landscape. Such a walk attracts many people year round and circulates money back into the local community as tourists stop off in local shops.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.bordnamona.ie/company/our-businesses/powergen/bord-na-monas-wind-farms/ |title=Our Wind Farms |work=Bord na M\u00f3na|accessdate=1 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Grid study in Ireland===\nAn Irish study of the grid indicates that it would be feasible to accommodate 42% (of demand) renewables\nin the electricity mix.<ref name='IrishPR'>{{cite web|url=http://www.dcenr.gov.ie/Press+Releases/2008/Study+shows+Ireland+can+be+world+leader+in+renewable+energy.htm |title=Study shows Ireland can be world leader in renewable energy |accessdate=2008-10-20 |date=January 2008 |work=Department of Communications, Energy and National Resources |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120321220558/http://www.dcenr.gov.ie/Press%2BReleases/2008/Study%2Bshows%2BIreland%2Bcan%2Bbe%2Bworld%2Bleader%2Bin%2Brenewable%2Benergy.htm |archivedate=21 March 2012 }}</ref>  This acceptable level of renewable penetration was found in what the study called Scenario 5, provided 47% of electrical capacity (different from demand) with the following mix of renewable energies:\n\n* 6,000 MW wind\n* 360 MW base load renewables\n* 285 MW additional variable renewables (other intermittent sources)\n\nThe study cautions that various assumptions were made that \"may have understated dispatch restrictions, resulting in an underestimation of operational costs, required wind curtailment, and CO<sub>2</sub> emissions\" and that \"The limitations of the study may overstate the technical feasibility of the portfolios analyzed...\"\n\nScenario 6, which proposed renewables providing 59% of electrical capacity and 54% of demand had problems.  Scenario 6 proposed the following mix of renewable energies:\n\n* 8,000 MW wind\n* 392 MW base load renewables\n* 1,685 MW additional variable renewables (other intermittent sources)\n\nThe study found that for Scenario 6, \"a significant number of hours characterized by extreme system situations occurred where load and reserve requirements could not be met.  The results of the network study indicated that for such extreme renewable penetration scenarios, a system re-design is required, rather than a reinforcement exercise.\"  The study declined to analyze the cost effectiveness of the required changes because \"determination of costs and benefits had become extremely dependent on the assumptions made\" and this uncertainty would have impacted the robustness of the results.<ref name='All_Island_Grid_Overview'>{{cite web |url=http://www.dcenr.gov.ie/NR/rdonlyres/E20F6E3D-8724-4E39-B315-0670B8C9841E/0/AllIslandGridStudyStudyOverviewJan08a2.pdf |title=All Island Grid Study |accessdate=2008-10-15 |date=January 2008 |pages=3\u20135, 15 |work=Department of Communications, Energy and Natural Resources |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090318231419/http://www.dcenr.gov.ie/NR/rdonlyres/E20F6E3D-8724-4E39-B315-0670B8C9841E/0/AllIslandGridStudyStudyOverviewJan08a2.pdf |archive-date=18 March 2009 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Ireland|Energy}}\n{{div col}}\n*[[List of wind farms]]\n*[[List of offshore wind farms in the Irish Sea]]\n*[[Renewable energy in the Republic of Ireland]]\n*[[Renewable energy]]\n*[[Wind turbine]]\n*[[Nuclear energy in Ireland]]\n*[[Renewable energy by country]]{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[http://www.sei.ie/ www.sei.ie] - Sustainable Energy Ireland, Ireland's national energy agency.\n*[http://www.iwea.ie/ www.iwea.ie] - Irish Wind Energy Association\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100714133354/http://www.gepower.com/businesses/ge_wind_energy/en/downloads/arklow_infosheet_final.pdf Arklow Bank Wind Park, GE Brochure] (PDF)\n*[http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2012/10/9/1349794960947/Ireland-wind-power-001.jpg 2012 Regional map of wind farms]<!--from http://www.guardian.co.uk/environment/2012/oct/08/wind-farms-ireland-uk-electricity-->\n{{Wind power}}\n{{Wind power by country}}\n{{Renewable energy by country}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wind Power In The Republic Of Ireland}}\n[[Category:Wind power in the Republic of Ireland| ]]\n", "name_user": "Alistair1978", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wind_power_in_the_Republic_of_Ireland"}
{"title_page": "Loop Service", "text_new": "{{Distinguish|text=the [[Loop Trolley]] in St. Louis}}\n{{Infobox rail line\n| name             = Loop Service\n| other_name       = {{plainlist}}\n* A Loop/B Loop\n* Central Loop Line (2012\u20132015)\n{{endplainlist}}\n| color            = {{TMTC color|B}}\n| color2           = {{TMTC color|A}}\n| logo             = Portland Streetcar symbol.svg\n| logo_width      = 30px\n| image            = Streetcar on Tilikum Crossing with fog-shrouded hills in background, 11-2015.jpg\n| image_width      = 250px\n| image_alt        = \n| caption          = A B Loop streetcar on Tilikum Crossing in 2015\n| type             = [[Streetcar]]\n| system           = [[Portland Streetcar]]\n| status           = Operational\n| locale           = [[Portland, Oregon]], U.S.\n| start            = \n| end              = \n| stations         = 52\n| routes           = 2\n| daily_ridership  = {{plainlist}}\n* '''A Loop:''' 3,612\n* '''B Loop:''' 3,064\n{{endplainlist}}{{br}}({{as of|2018|September|lc=yes}})<ref name=\"portland-streetcar-ridership-counts-2018-09\">{{cite news |url=https://storage.googleapis.com/streetcar/files/Ridership-Counts-2018-09.pdf |title=Portland Streetcar Ridership Counts, July 2015 - Present (By Fiscal Year) |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |date=September 2018 |access-date=March 18, 2019}}</ref>\n{{endplainlist}}\n| ridership2       =\n| open             = {{start date|2012|09|22}}\n| event1label      = \n| event1           = \n| event2label      = \n| event2           = \n| event3label      = \n| event3           = \n| owner            = [[Government of Portland, Oregon|City of Portland]]\n| operator         = Portland Streetcar, Inc.{{br}}[[TriMet]]\n| character        = [[At-grade]], mixed between [[street running]] and exclusive lane\n| depot            = \n| stock            = \n| linelength       = {{convert|4.4|mi|km|abbr=on}} (per direction)\n| tracklength_mi   = \n| tracks           = \n| gauge            = {{Track gauge|ussg|allk=on}}\n| old_gauge        = \n| load_gauge       = \n| minradius        = \n| racksystem       = \n| routenumber      = \n| linenumber       = \n| electrification  = 750 [[Volt|V]] [[Direct Current|DC]], [[overhead line|overhead catenary]]\n| speed_mph        = \n| elevation_ft     = \n| website          = \n| map              = {{Portland Streetcar CL Line}}\n| map_name         = Route diagram\n| map_state        = collapsed\n}}\nThe '''Loop Service''' is a [[streetcar]] [[circle route|circle line]] in [[Portland, Oregon]], United States, that is part of the [[Portland Streetcar]] system. Operated by Portland Streetcar, Inc. and [[TriMet]], it consists of two distinct services: the '''A Loop''', which runs [[clockwise]], and the '''B Loop''', which runs counterclockwise. Each service travels a {{convert|4.4|mi|km|1|adj=on}} loop between [[Downtown Portland, Oregon|downtown Portland]] and the [[Central Eastside, Portland, Oregon|Central Eastside]], crossing the [[Willamette River]] on the [[Broadway Bridge (Portland)|Broadway Bridge]] in the north and [[Tilikum Crossing]] in the south. The line connects Portland's downtown, [[Pearl District, Portland, Oregon|Pearl District]], [[South Waterfront, Portland, Oregon|South Waterfront]], and [[Lloyd District, Portland, Oregon|Lloyd District]]. It serves the city's various landmarks and institutions, including the [[Rose Quarter, Portland, Oregon|Rose Quarter]], the [[Oregon Convention Center]], the [[Oregon Museum of Science and Industry]] (OMSI), [[Oregon Health and Science University]] (OHSU), and [[Portland State University]] (PSU).\n\nPortland city officials first proposed building an eastside streetcar line in 1997, at the same time the city council authorized the construction of the [[NS Line|first streetcar line]] in downtown. After several years of planning, the city council adopted the Eastside Streetcar Alignment Study in 2003. Upon its inaugural service in 2012, the Loop Service was known as the '''Central Loop Line''' ('''CL Line'''). It initially ran from Southwest Market Street in downtown Portland to OMSI via the Pearl District. It was re-branded to its current name upon the opening of Tilikum Crossing bridge in 2015.<ref name=\"PS-Loop\">{{cite web|title=Portland Streetcar Loop Service |url=http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/node/193 |publisher=[[Portland Streetcar]] |accessdate=September 7, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150806004043/http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/node/193 |archivedate=August 6, 2015 |df= }}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Planning===\n[[File:Broadway Bridge west end.jpg|thumb|left|The Broadway Bridge in 2009, prior to the installation of streetcar tracks]]\n\nPlans to expand the Portland Streetcar east of the [[Willamette River]] emerged in July 1997, at the same time the [[Government of Portland, Oregon|Portland City Council]] authorized the construction of the system's [[NS Line|first line]] on the west side between [[Northwest District, Portland, Oregon|Northwest Portland]] and [[Portland State University|PSU]]. During this time, the council also voted to fund a $16.7&nbsp;million retrofitting of the [[Hawthorne Bridge]],<ref>{{cite news |last=Stewart |first=Bill |title=Closure launches bridge make over |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=January 22, 1998 |page=D2}}</ref> which they had anticipated would carry a future streetcar line between [[Oregon Museum of Science and Industry|OMSI]] and the [[Oregon Convention Center]]. This line was one of many proposed by the Buckman Neighborhood Association for the east side.<ref>{{cite news |last=Stewart |first=Bill |title=Streetcars will return to Portland; the city council votes to pay for a westside loop of streetcars described as cheaper than light rail |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=July 31, 1997 |page=D1}}</ref> The Hawthorne Bridge reopened in April 1999, with the outer-lane decks rebuilt to accommodate notches for rails.<ref>{{cite news |last=Stewart |first=Bill |title=Wait no more: Sunday makrs Hawthorne Bridge reopening |date=April 24, 1999 |newspaper=The Oregonian |page=C1}}</ref> In July 2001, another streetcar plan was proposed as part of the Lloyd District Development Strategy.<ref name=\"development-strategy-2001\">{{cite web |url=https://prosperportland.us/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/Lloyd-District-Development-Strategy-Full-2001-07-27.pdf |title=Lloyd District Development Strategy |publisher=[[Prosper Portland|Portland Development Commission]] |date=July 27, 2001 |access-date=August 29, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Leeson |first=Fred |title=Portland grand plans works in works in Lloyd District |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=July 17, 2001 |page=B3}}</ref> This strategy sought the addition of streetcars to the [[Lloyd District, Portland, Oregon|Lloyd District]], which was already being served by buses and [[MAX Light Rail]],<ref name=\"development-strategy-2001\"/>{{rp|20}} to create a [[transit hub]] by adding lines on Broadway and Weilder avenues.<ref name=\"development-strategy-2001\"/>{{rp|26}} The extension would connect with the west side via the [[Broadway Bridge (Portland, Oregon)|Broadway Bridge]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Leeson |first=Fred |title=New streetcar route follows different mission |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=July 20, 2001 |page=24}}</ref> This plan was supported by concurrent efforts to revitalize nearby [[Rose Quarter]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Leeson |first=Fred |title=Vision for Rose Quarter outlined |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=July 13, 2001 |page=A1}}</ref>\n\nIn a series of meetings that began in February 2003, an advisory committee composed of eastside residents urged extending this proposed Broadway\u2013Weilder alignment up to 21st Avenue. Meanwhile, Portland Streetcar officials, amid [[TriMet]] plans to construct a new Willamette River crossing as part of a [[MAX Orange Line|MAX extension to Milwaukie]], suggested routing the streetcar along this new bridge proposal instead of the Hawthorne Bridge.<ref>{{cite news |last=Leeson |first=Fred |title=Streetcar officials seek Eastside desire |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=February 17, 2003 |page=E2}}</ref> The city council, with backing from [[Multnomah County, Oregon|Multnomah County]] commissioners, adopted the Eastside Streetcar Alignment Study in June 2003.<ref name=\"eastside-study\">{{cite web |title=Eastside Streetcar Alignment Study |date=June 25, 2003 |publisher=City of Portland Office of Transportation |url=https://scholarsbank.uoregon.edu/xmlui/bitstream/handle/1794/5259/Portland_Eastside_Streetcar_Study.pdf |access-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref> The study outlined a three-phased eastside loop project that ran from the Broadway Bridge to the Lloyd District, then south through Grand Avenue and [[Oregon Route 99E|Martin Luther King Jr. Boulevard]] to Hawthorne Boulevard. A southern crossing back to the west side depended upon whether the new bridge would be constructed, leaving that section undetermined at the time.<ref>{{cite news |last=Leeson |first=Fred |title=Streetcar backers propose loop through Inner Eastside |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=June 6, 2003 |page=D2}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Stern |first1=Henry |last2=Nkrumah |first2=Wade |title=City Council watch |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=June 26, 2003 |page=C2}}</ref>\n\n===Funding and construction===\n\n[[Metro (Oregon regional government)|Metro]] regional government approved the streetcar extension in July 2006 followed by the city council in September 2007.<ref>{{cite news |last=McGrain |first=Maureen |title=Metro says yes to expansion for streetcar |newspaper=Portland Business Journal |date=July 28, 2006 |url=http://portland.bizjournals.com/portland/stories/2006/07/31/story11.html |accessdate=May 20, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"extension-green-light\">{{cite news |last=Mayer |first=James |date=September 7, 2007 |title=Streetcar extension gets green light |newspaper=The Oregonian |page=D1}}</ref> The total cost of the project was $148.3{{nbsp}}million (equivalent to ${{Format price|{{Inflation|US-GDP|148300000|2012}}}} in {{Inflation-year|US-GDP}} dollars), including the cost to purchase additional vehicles. Just over half would be paid for with federal funds.<ref name=\"wweek20120822\">{{cite web |title=Slow Ride |url=https://www.wweek.com/portland/article-19584-slow_ride.html |first=Aaron |last=Mesh |date=August 22, 2012 |newspaper=[[Willamette Week]] |accessdate=August 29, 2012}}</ref> The city council committed to allocating $27{{nbsp}}million of city funds.<ref name=\"extension-green-light\"/> $20{{nbsp}}million from the state, $15.5{{nbsp}}million from a Local Improvement District, and a combination of various other local or regional sources completed the locally matched financing.<ref name=\"factsheetMay2010\">{{cite web |title=Portland Streetcar Loop fact sheet (May 2010) |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |url=http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/pdf/loop_fact_sheet_and_map_201005.pdf |accessdate=August 30, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100821075510/http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/pdf/loop_fact_sheet_and_map_201005.pdf |archive-date=August 21, 2010 |url-status=unfit}}</ref> On April 30, 2009, U.S. [[United States Secretary of Transportation|Transportation Secretary]] [[Ray LaHood]] announced $75{{nbsp}}million in federal funding for the project, the full amount that had been requested by Portland. This allocation, secured in large part through the efforts of Oregon [[United States House of Representatives|Representatives]] [[Earl Blumenauer]] and [[Peter DeFazio]], was the largest and final component of the financing plan and meant the project could proceed with construction.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pope |first1=Charles |last2=Rivera |first2=Dylan |title=Feds approve $75 million for streetcar expansion |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=April 30, 2009 |url=http://www.oregonlive.com/news/index.ssf/2009/04/feds_approve_75_million_for_st.html |accessdate=September 10, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121005165644/http://www.oregonlive.com/news/index.ssf/2009/04/feds_approve_75_million_for_st.html |archive-date=October 5, 2012 |url-status=unfit}}</ref><ref name=\"Fedsgive\">{{cite news |title=Feds give $75 million for Oregon streetcar |newspaper=Portland Business Journal |date=April 30, 2009 |url=http://www.bizjournals.com/portland/stories/2009/04/27/daily46.html?surround=lfn |accessdate=September 10, 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[File:United Streetcar 10T3 prototype for Portland.jpg|thumb|right|Unveiling of the United Streetcar 10T3 prototype in July 2009]]\n\nIn 2005, the [[United States Congress|U.S. Congress]] approved a spending bill that included $4{{nbsp}}million for a locally-produced streetcar vehicle.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.portlandtribune.com/news/story.php?story_id=31153 |last=Hamilton |first=Don |title=Iron firm forges streetcar desire |newspaper=[[Portland Tribune]] |date=August 5, 2005 |access-date=April 4, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120331125621/https://www.portlandtribune.com/news/story.php?story_id=31153 |archive-date=March 31, 2012}}</ref> That money went to [[Oregon Iron Works]], which created the subsidiary [[United Streetcar]] upon being awarded the contract to build new streetcars for the Portland Streetcar.<ref name=\"streetcarcontract\">{{cite news |author=<!--no by line; staff writer(s)--> |title=Oregon Iron Works gets contract for streetcar |date=January 26, 2007 |newspaper=[[Portland Business Journal]] |url=https://portland.bizjournals.com/portland/stories/2007/01/22/daily45.html |accessdate=December 19, 2012}}</ref> In May 2009, United Streetcar delivered its first prototype to Portland for testing on existing tracks; it was the first U.S.-built streetcar in nearly 60 years.<ref name=\"trib-2009may14\">{{cite news |last=MacKinnon |first=Mary |title=Streetcars soon to be made in Oregon |newspaper=[[Portland Tribune]] |date=May 14, 2009<!--(later re-dated May 13)--> |url=http://portlandtribune.com/component/content/article?id=49492 |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref> That August, the city signed a $20{{nbsp}}million contract to purchase six new streetcars from the manufacturer for the eastside extension.<ref name=\"Oreg14Aug09\">{{cite news |last=Rivera |first=Dylan |title=Portland inks $20 million deal for locally made streetcars |date=August 14, 2009 |newspaper=The Oregonian |url=http://www.oregonlive.com/news/index.ssf/2009/08/portland_inks_20_million_deal.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090817123910/http://www.oregonlive.com/news/index.ssf/2009/08/portland_inks_20_million_deal.html |archivedate=17 August 2009 |url-status=live |accessdate=June 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\nGroundbreaking for the Eastside Streetcar Loop project took place on June 25, 2009. The city selected [[Stacy and Witbeck]] to be the project's general contractor and actual construction began the following year.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.opb.org/news/article/construction-begins-eastside-streetcar-loop/ |last=Baer |first=April |title=Construction Begins On Eastside Streetcar Loop |publisher=[[Oregon Public Broadcasting]] |date=June 25, 2009 |access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref> Across the alignment, crews laid tracks in three- to four-block increments; by February 2010, they were laying tracks on Northeast Grand Avenue.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://djcoregon.com/news/2010/02/09/streetcar-loop-project/ |title=Streetcar Loop Project |last=Carter |first=Dan |publisher=[[Daily Journal of Commerce]] |date=February 9, 2010 |access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref> The Broadway Bridge was closed to all traffic from July 19 to September 3, 2010 to be renovated.<ref>{{cite news |last=Rose |first=Joseph |title=Portland \u2013 Broadway Bridge will close |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=July 18, 2010}}</ref> To maintain the existing weight of the bridge (this was necessary to allow the bridge to continue lifting its spans) and simultaneously add tracks, lighter fiber-reinforced concrete replaced the deck.<ref name=\"streetcar work\">{{cite news|last=Rose|first=Joseph |title=Streetcar work shutting down Broadway Bridge |date=July 5, 2010 <!--(July 4 online edition)--> |newspaper=The Oregonian |page=A10 |url=https://blog.oregonlive.com/commuting/2010/07/streetcar_work_shuts_broadway.html |accessdate=November 9, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"wrap-up-broadway\">{{cite news |url=https://djcoregon.com/news/2011/02/18/streetcar-work-almost-finished-on-broadway-bridge/ |last=Vorenberg |first=Sue |title=Streetcar work wraps up on Broadway Bridge |publisher=Daily Journal of Commerce |date=February 18, 2011 |access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref> In the [[Pearl District, Portland, Oregon|Pearl District]], sections of two former two-way streets\u2014Northwest Lovejoy and Northwest Northrup\u2014were converted into one-way streets following the addition of streetcar tracks. Work completed in this section upon the reopening of the Lovejoy ramp on the west end of the Broadway Bridge in November 2010.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://djcoregon.com/news/2010/11/05/pearl-streets-reopen-with-changed-traffic-patterns/ |last=Vorenberg |first=Sue |title=Pearl streets reopen with changed traffic patterns |publisher=Daily Journal of Commerce |date=November 5, 2010 |access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref> In Southeast Portland, crews built a {{convert|425|ft|m|adj=mid|-long}} bridge that led the streetcar to OMSI, the project's eastern terminus.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://djcoregon.com/news/2010/12/22/portland-streetcar-flyover-bridge-near-omsi/ |last=Carter |first=Dan |title=Portland Streetcar flyover bridge near OMSI |publisher=Daily Journal of Commerce |date=December 22, 2010 |access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2011, the city council agreed to contractual changes that reduced the number of streetcars on order from the original six to five.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://djcoregon.com/news/2011/07/20/eastside-streetcar-loop-will-be-delayed-number-of-cars-reduced/ |last=Webber |first=Angela |title=Eastside streetcar loop will be delayed, number of cars reduced |publisher=Daily Journal of Commerce |date=July 20, 2011 |access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref> United Streetcar had depended on [[Czech Republic|Czech]] firm [[\u0160koda]], which built the system's first streetcars, to build the new streetcars' propulsion system but these failed to meet Portland Streetcar's standards. City officials opted instead to source the propulsion system from Wisconsin-based [[Rockwell Automation]], but this was still being developed at the time. Knowing that waiting on Rockwell would cause more delays, city officials pursued [[Austria]]n manufacturer Elin to produce one for the prototype. All of these changes delayed the project and raised the cost of manufacturing.<ref name=\"oreg-2011jul19\">{{cite news |last=Schmidt |first=Brad |title=Portland's $148.3 million eastside streetcar project delayed five months, includes five streetcars instead of six |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=July 19, 2011 |url=http://www.oregonlive.com/portland/index.ssf/2011/07/portlands_1483_million_eastsid.html |accessdate=September 10, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Opening===\n[[File:Barber Block sunlit with streetcar, 2012.jpg|thumb|left|Car 015 in front of the [[Barber Block]] on Southeast Grand Avenue in 2012]] \n\nThe Central Loop Line began service on September 22, 2012, running from Southwest Market Street to the [[Oregon Museum of Science and Industry]] (OMSI) via the [[Pearl District, Portland, Oregon|Pearl District]].<ref name=\"PS-History\">{{cite web|title=Streetcar History |url=http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/node/33 |publisher=Portland Streetcar |accessdate=September 7, 2015 |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203013400/http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/node/33 |archivedate=December 3, 2013 |df= }}</ref> The {{convert|3.35|mi|km|adj=mid|-long}} line cost $148.3 million to construct and opened five months late,<ref>{{cite news |last=Schmidt |first=Brad |date=July 19, 2011 |title=Portland's $148.3 million eastside streetcar project delayed five months, includes five streetcars instead of six |url=http://www.oregonlive.com/portland/index.ssf/2011/07/portlands_1483_million_eastsid.html |newspaper=[[The Oregonian]] |accessdate=September 17, 2015}}</ref> with 18-minute frequencies instead of the planned 15 minutes due to funding cuts by [[TriMet]] and the [[Government of Portland, Oregon|City of Portland]] as well as delays in streetcar delivery from [[United Streetcar]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Rose |first=Joseph |authorlink=Joseph Rose (journalist) |date=September 21, 2012 |title=Portland Streetcar's eastside loop gets off to hobbled start Saturday |url=http://blog.oregonlive.com/commuting/2012/09/portland_streetcars_eastside_l.html |newspaper=The Oregonian |accessdate=September 7, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=October 5, 2012 |title=Portland Streetcar Introduces \u2018Central Loop\u2019 Service |url=http://newsmanager.commpartners.com/aptapt/issues/2012-10-05/3.html |work=Passenger Transport |publisher=[[American Public Transportation Association]] |accessdate=September 8, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn August 30, 2015, a new temporary schedule eliminated the CL Line in favor of the A Loop and B Loop, extended from SW 10th and Market along the NS Line south to SW Moody Avenue & SW Meade Street in the [[South Waterfront, Portland, Oregon|South Waterfront]]. Streetcars began operating across the new [[Tilikum Crossing]] transit bridge on that date, but not carrying passengers across the bridge during a two-week transitional phase which was referred to as \"pre-revenue service\".<ref name=\"PS-Loop\"/> The line was formally re-branded as the Loop Service on September 12, 2015, when the opening of the Tilikum Crossing to the public permitted streetcars to begin carrying passengers on the route section across the bridge.<ref name=\"PS-Loop\"/><ref name=\"PS-History\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Vincent |first=John M. |date=September 8, 2015 |title=Routes, fares change with expanded streetcar service |url=http://portlandtribune.com/pt/9-news/271906-147003-routes-fares-change-with-expanded-streetcar-service |newspaper=[[The Portland Tribune]] |publisher=[[Pamplin Media Group]] |page=A3 |accessdate=August 23, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151128143529/http://portlandtribune.com/pt/9-news/271906-147003-routes-fares-change-with-expanded-streetcar-service |archivedate=November 28, 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n{{clear left}}\n\n==Route==\n[[File:A Lloyd via Peral (21612375879).jpg|thumb|right|An A Loop streetcar on Tilikum Crossing in 2015]]\n[[File:Portland Streetcar car 023 at west end of Broadway Bridge in 2016.jpg|thumb|right|A B Loop streetcar crossing the Broadway Bridge in 2016]]\n\n===Stations===\n\nThe Loop Service serves 52 stations, of which 24 are shared with the NS Line.<ref name=\"maps-schedules\">{{cite web |url=https://portlandstreetcar.org/schedules |title=Maps + Schedules \u2013 Portland Streetcar |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |access-date=March 18, 2019}}</ref> Each platform is equipped with a [[ticket vending machine]], [[passenger information system|real-time display]] system, and line information signs.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://portlandstreetcar.org/ride-guide/how-to-ride |title=Ride Guide |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |access-date=April 1, 2019}}</ref> All stations are [[Accessibility|accessible]] to users with [[Physical disability|limited mobility]].<ref name=\"accessibility-info\">{{cite web |url=http://portlandstreetcar.org/node/8 |title=Accessibility Info |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |access-date=June 6, 2019 |archive-date=February 1, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120201000132/http://portlandstreetcar.org/node/8 |url-status=unfit}}</ref> Connections to MAX Light Rail are available at 10 stops across the line.<ref name=\"Transit Mall map\">{{cite map |url=https://trimet.org/maps/pdf/citycenter.pdf |title=Portland City Center and Transit Mall |publisher=TriMet |access-date=July 30, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190210193921/https://trimet.org/maps/pdf/citycenter.pdf |archive-date=February 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! colspan=2 | Station\n! rowspan=2 | Neighborhood\n! rowspan=2 |Connections and notes<ref name=\"maps-schedules\"/>\n|-\n! A Loop{{br}}(clockwise)\n! B Loop{{br}}(counterclockwise)\n|-\n| \u2014\n| Northwest 10th & Northrup\n| rowspan=\"6\" align=\"center\" | [[Pearl District, Portland, Oregon|Pearl District]]\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}\n|-\n| \u2014\n| Northwest 11th & Marshall\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Northwest 9th & Lovejoy\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Northwest 10th & Johnson\n| Northwest 11th & Johnson\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}\n|-\n| Northwest 10th & Glisan\n| Northwest 11th & Glisan\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}\n|-\n| Northwest 10th & Couch\n| Northwest 11th & Couch\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}{{br}}Serves [[First Regiment Armory Annex|The Armory]], [[Powell's Books|Powell's City of Books]]\n|-\n| Southwest 10th & Alder\n| Southwest 11th & Alder\n| rowspan=\"10\" align=\"center\" | [[Downtown Portland, Oregon|Downtown]]\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}\n|-\n| Central Library\n| Southwest 11th & Taylor\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}; {{rint|light rail|link=MAX Light Rail}} [[Library/Southwest 9th Avenue and Galleria/Southwest 10th Avenue stations|Library and Galleria stations]]: [[MAX Blue Line|Blue]], [[MAX Red Line|Red]] lines{{br}}Serves [[Central Library (Portland, Oregon)|Central Library]]\n|-\n| Art Museum\n| Southwest 11th & Jefferson\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}{{br}}Serves [[Portland Art Museum]]\n|-\n| Southwest 10th & Clay\n| Southwest 11th & Clay\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}\n|-\n| Southwest Park & Mill\n| Southwest Park & Market\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}{{br}}Serves [[South Park Blocks]]\n|-\n| \u2014\n| Southwest 5th & Market\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}{{br}}Serves [[Portland State University]]\n|-\n| PSU Urban Center\n| Southwest 5th & Montgomery\n| 