br}}Serves [[Oregon Convention Center]]\n|-\n| Northeast Oregon & Grand\n| Northeast Grand & Holladay\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Northeast 7th & Holladay\n| Northeast Grand & Multnomah\n| {{rint|light rail|link=MAX Light Rail}} [[Northeast 7th Avenue station]]: [[MAX Blue Line|Blue]], [[MAX Green Line|Green]], and [[MAX Red Line|Red]] lines\n|-\n| Northeast 7th & Halsey\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Northeast Weidler & Grand\n| Northeast Grand & Broadway\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Northeast Weidler & 2nd\n| Northeast Broadway & 2nd\n| \u2014\n|-\n| North Weidler & Ross\n| North Broadway & Ross\n| \u2014\n|}\n\n==Service==\n\nThe Loop Service operates from 5:30&nbsp;a.m. to 11:30&nbsp;p.m. on weekdays, from 7:30&nbsp;a.m. to 11:30&nbsp;p.m. on Saturdays, and from 7:30&nbsp;a.m. to 10:30&nbsp;p.m. on Sundays. Frequencies in each direction range from 15 minutes between 10:00&nbsp;a.m. and 7:00&nbsp;pm on weekdays and Saturdays to 20 minutes on Sundays.<ref name=\"Schedule\">{{cite web |date=August 30, 2015 |title=Streetcar Schedule |url=http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/node/3 |publisher=Portland Streetcar |accessdate=September 29, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Attached KML |display=title,inline}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20150806004043/http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/node/193 Portland Streetcar Loop Service]\n*[http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/node/3 Portland Streetcar schedule]\n\n{{Portland Transit}}\n{{Streetcars Portland Oregon}}\n{{Portal bar|Oregon|Trains|Transport}}\n\n[[Category:2012 establishments in Oregon]]\n[[Category:Passenger rail transportation in Oregon]]\n[[Category:Railway lines opened in 2012]]\n[[Category:Streetcars in Oregon]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Portland, Oregon]]\n[[Category:TriMet]]\n", "text_old": "{{Distinguish|text=the [[Loop Trolley]] in St. Louis}}\n{{Infobox rail line\n| name             = Loop Service\n| other_name       = {{plainlist}}\n* A Loop/B Loop\n* Central Loop Line (2012\u20132015)\n{{endplainlist}}\n| color            = {{TMTC color|B}}\n| color2           = {{TMTC color|A}}\n| logo             = Portland Streetcar symbol.svg\n| logo_width      = 30px\n| image            = Streetcar on Tilikum Crossing with fog-shrouded hills in background, 11-2015.jpg\n| image_width      = 250px\n| image_alt        = \n| caption          = A B Loop streetcar on Tilikum Crossing in 2015\n| type             = [[Streetcar]]\n| system           = [[Portland Streetcar]]\n| status           = Operational\n| locale           = [[Portland, Oregon]], U.S.\n| start            = \n| end              = \n| stations         = 52\n| routes           = 2\n| daily_ridership  = {{plainlist}}\n* '''A Loop:''' 3,612\n* '''B Loop:''' 3,064\n{{endplainlist}}{{br}}({{as of|2018|September|lc=yes}})<ref name=\"portland-streetcar-ridership-counts-2018-09\">{{cite news |url=https://storage.googleapis.com/streetcar/files/Ridership-Counts-2018-09.pdf |title=Portland Streetcar Ridership Counts, July 2015 - Present (By Fiscal Year) |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |date=September 2018 |access-date=March 18, 2019}}</ref>\n{{endplainlist}}\n| ridership2       =\n| open             = {{start date|2012|09|22}}\n| event1label      = \n| event1           = \n| event2label      = \n| event2           = \n| event3label      = \n| event3           = \n| owner            = [[Government of Portland, Oregon|City of Portland]]\n| operator         = Portland Streetcar, Inc.{{br}}[[TriMet]]\n| character        = [[At-grade]], mixed between [[street running]] and exclusive lane\n| depot            = \n| stock            = \n| linelength       = {{convert|4.4|mi|km|abbr=on}} (per direction)\n| tracklength_mi   = \n| tracks           = \n| gauge            = {{Track gauge|ussg|allk=on}}\n| old_gauge        = \n| load_gauge       = \n| minradius        = \n| racksystem       = \n| routenumber      = \n| linenumber       = \n| electrification  = 750 [[Volt|V]] [[Direct Current|DC]], [[overhead line|overhead catenary]]\n| speed_mph        = \n| elevation_ft     = \n| website          = \n| map              = {{Portland Streetcar CL Line}}\n| map_name         = Route diagram\n| map_state        = collapsed\n}}\nThe '''Loop Service''' is a [[streetcar]] [[circle route|circle line]] in [[Portland, Oregon]], United States, that is part of the [[Portland Streetcar]] system. Operated by Portland Streetcar, Inc. and [[TriMet]], it consists of two distinct services: the '''A Loop''', which runs [[clockwise]], and the '''B Loop''', which runs counterclockwise. Each service travels a {{convert|4.4|mi|km|1|adj=on}} loop between [[Downtown Portland, Oregon|downtown Portland]] and the [[Central Eastside, Portland, Oregon|Central Eastside]], crossing the [[Willamette River]] on the [[Broadway Bridge (Portland)|Broadway Bridge]] in the north and [[Tilikum Crossing]] in the south. The line connects Portland's downtown, [[Pearl District, Portland, Oregon|Pearl District]], [[South Waterfront, Portland, Oregon|South Waterfront]], and [[Lloyd District, Portland, Oregon|Lloyd District]]. It serves the city's various landmarks and institutions, including the [[Rose Quarter, Portland, Oregon|Rose Quarter]], the [[Oregon Convention Center]], the [[Oregon Museum of Science and Industry]] (OMSI), [[Oregon Health and Science University]] (OHSU), and [[Portland State University]] (PSU).\n\nPortland city officials first proposed building an eastside streetcar line in 1997, at the same time the city council authorized the construction of the [[NS Line|first streetcar line]] in downtown. After several years of planning, the city council adopted the Eastside Streetcar Alignment Study in 2003. Upon its inaugural service in 2012, the Loop Service was known as the '''Central Loop Line''' ('''CL Line'''). It initially ran from Southwest Market Street in downtown Portland to OMSI via the Pearl District. It was re-branded to its current name upon the opening of Tilikum Crossing bridge in 2015.<ref name=\"PS-Loop\">{{cite web|title=Portland Streetcar Loop Service |url=http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/node/193 |publisher=[[Portland Streetcar]] |accessdate=September 7, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150806004043/http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/node/193 |archivedate=August 6, 2015 |df= }}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Planning===\n[[File:Broadway Bridge west end.jpg|thumb|left|The Broadway Bridge in 2009, prior to the installation of streetcar tracks]]\n\nPlans to expand the Portland Streetcar east of the [[Willamette River]] emerged in July 1997, at the same time the [[Government of Portland, Oregon|Portland City Council]] authorized the construction of the system's [[NS Line|first line]] on the west side between [[Northwest District, Portland, Oregon|Northwest Portland]] and [[Portland State University|PSU]]. During this time, the council also voted to fund a $16.7&nbsp;million retrofitting of the [[Hawthorne Bridge]],<ref>{{cite news |last=Stewart |first=Bill |title=Closure launches bridge make over |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=January 22, 1998 |page=D2}}</ref> which they had anticipated would carry a future streetcar line between [[Oregon Museum of Science and Industry|OMSI]] and the [[Oregon Convention Center]]. This line was one of many proposed by the Buckman Neighborhood Association for the east side.<ref>{{cite news |last=Stewart |first=Bill |title=Streetcars will return to Portland; the city council votes to pay for a westside loop of streetcars described as cheaper than light rail |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=July 31, 1997 |page=D1}}</ref> The Hawthorne Bridge reopened in April 1999, with the outer-lane decks rebuilt to accommodate notches for rails.<ref>{{cite news |last=Stewart |first=Bill |title=Wait no more: Sunday makrs Hawthorne Bridge reopening |date=April 24, 1999 |newspaper=The Oregonian |page=C1}}</ref> In July 2001, another streetcar plan was proposed as part of the Lloyd District Development Strategy.<ref name=\"development-strategy-2001\">{{cite web |url=https://prosperportland.us/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/Lloyd-District-Development-Strategy-Full-2001-07-27.pdf |title=Lloyd District Development Strategy |publisher=[[Prosper Portland|Portland Development Commission]] |date=July 27, 2001 |access-date=August 29, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Leeson |first=Fred |title=Portland grand plans works in works in Lloyd District |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=July 17, 2001 |page=B3}}</ref> This strategy sought the addition of streetcars to the [[Lloyd District, Portland, Oregon|Lloyd District]], which was already being served by buses and [[MAX Light Rail]],<ref name=\"development-strategy-2001\"/>{{rp|20}} to create a [[transit hub]] by adding lines on Broadway and Weilder avenues.<ref name=\"development-strategy-2001\"/>{{rp|26}} The extension would connect with the west side via the [[Broadway Bridge (Portland, Oregon)|Broadway Bridge]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Leeson |first=Fred |title=New streetcar route follows different mission |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=July 20, 2001 |page=24}}</ref> This plan was supported by concurrent efforts to revitalize nearby [[Rose Quarter]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Leeson |first=Fred |title=Vision for Rose Quarter outlined |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=July 13, 2001 |page=A1}}</ref>\n\nIn a series of meetings that began in February 2003, an advisory committee composed of eastside residents urged extending this proposed Broadway\u2013Weilder alignment up to 21st Avenue. Meanwhile, Portland Streetcar officials, amid [[TriMet]] plans to construct a new Willamette River crossing as part of a [[MAX Orange Line|MAX extension to Milwaukie]], suggested routing the streetcar along this new bridge proposal instead of the Hawthorne Bridge.<ref>{{cite news |last=Leeson |first=Fred |title=Streetcar officials seek Eastside desire |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=February 17, 2003 |page=E2}}</ref> The city council, with backing from [[Multnomah County, Oregon|Multnomah County]] commissioners, adopted the Eastside Streetcar Alignment Study in June 2003.<ref name=\"eastside-study\">{{cite web |title=Eastside Streetcar Alignment Study |date=June 25, 2003 |publisher=City of Portland Office of Transportation |url=https://scholarsbank.uoregon.edu/xmlui/bitstream/handle/1794/5259/Portland_Eastside_Streetcar_Study.pdf |access-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref> The study outlined a three-phased eastside loop project that ran from the Broadway Bridge to the Lloyd District, then south through Grand Avenue and [[Oregon Route 99E|Martin Luther King Jr. Boulevard]] to Hawthorne Boulevard. A southern crossing back to the west side depended upon whether the new bridge would be constructed, leaving that section undetermined at the time.<ref>{{cite news |last=Leeson |first=Fred |title=Streetcar backers propose loop through Inner Eastside |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=June 6, 2003 |page=D2}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Stern |first1=Henry |last2=Nkrumah |first2=Wade |title=City Council watch |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=June 26, 2003 |page=C2}}</ref>\n\n===Funding and construction===\n\n[[Metro (Oregon regional government)|Metro]] regional government approved the streetcar extension in July 2006 followed by the city council in September 2007.<ref>{{cite news |last=McGrain |first=Maureen |title=Metro says yes to expansion for streetcar |newspaper=Portland Business Journal |date=July 28, 2006 |url=http://portland.bizjournals.com/portland/stories/2006/07/31/story11.html |accessdate=May 20, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"extension-green-light\">{{cite news |last=Mayer |first=James |date=September 7, 2007 |title=Streetcar extension gets green light |newspaper=The Oregonian |page=D1}}</ref> The total cost of the project was $148.3{{nbsp}}million (equivalent to ${{Format price|{{Inflation|US-GDP|148300000|2012}}}} in {{Inflation-year|US-GDP}} dollars), including the cost to purchase additional vehicles. Just over half would be paid for with federal funds.<ref name=\"wweek20120822\">{{cite web |title=Slow Ride |url=https://www.wweek.com/portland/article-19584-slow_ride.html |first=Aaron |last=Mesh |date=August 22, 2012 |newspaper=[[Willamette Week]] |accessdate=August 29, 2012}}</ref> The city council committed to allocating $27{{nbsp}}million of city funds.<ref name=\"extension-green-light\"/> $20{{nbsp}}million from the state, $15.5{{nbsp}}million from a Local Improvement District, and a combination of various other local or regional sources completed the locally matched financing.<ref name=\"factsheetMay2010\">{{cite web |title=Portland Streetcar Loop fact sheet (May 2010) |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |url=http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/pdf/loop_fact_sheet_and_map_201005.pdf |accessdate=August 30, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100821075510/http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/pdf/loop_fact_sheet_and_map_201005.pdf |archive-date=August 21, 2010 |url-status=unfit}}</ref> On April 30, 2009, U.S. [[United States Secretary of Transportation|Transportation Secretary]] [[Ray LaHood]] announced $75{{nbsp}}million in federal funding for the project, the full amount that had been requested by Portland. This allocation, secured in large part through the efforts of Oregon [[United States House of Representatives|Representatives]] [[Earl Blumenauer]] and [[Peter DeFazio]], was the largest and final component of the financing plan and meant the project could proceed with construction.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pope |first1=Charles |last2=Rivera |first2=Dylan |title=Feds approve $75 million for streetcar expansion |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=April 30, 2009 |url=http://www.oregonlive.com/news/index.ssf/2009/04/feds_approve_75_million_for_st.html |accessdate=September 10, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121005165644/http://www.oregonlive.com/news/index.ssf/2009/04/feds_approve_75_million_for_st.html |archive-date=October 5, 2012 |url-status=unfit}}</ref><ref name=\"Fedsgive\">{{cite news |title=Feds give $75 million for Oregon streetcar |newspaper=Portland Business Journal |date=April 30, 2009 |url=http://www.bizjournals.com/portland/stories/2009/04/27/daily46.html?surround=lfn |accessdate=September 10, 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[File:United Streetcar 10T3 prototype for Portland.jpg|thumb|right|Unveiling of the United Streetcar 10T3 prototype in July 2009]]\n\nIn 2005, the [[United States Congress|U.S. Congress]] approved a spending bill that included $4{{nbsp}}million for a locally-produced streetcar vehicle.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.portlandtribune.com/news/story.php?story_id=31153 |last=Hamilton |first=Don |title=Iron firm forges streetcar desire |newspaper=[[Portland Tribune]] |date=August 5, 2005 |access-date=April 4, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120331125621/https://www.portlandtribune.com/news/story.php?story_id=31153 |archive-date=March 31, 2012}}</ref> That money went to [[Oregon Iron Works]], which created the subsidiary [[United Streetcar]] upon being awarded the contract to build new streetcars for the Portland Streetcar.<ref name=\"streetcarcontract\">{{cite news |author=<!--no by line; staff writer(s)--> |title=Oregon Iron Works gets contract for streetcar |date=January 26, 2007 |newspaper=[[Portland Business Journal]] |url=https://portland.bizjournals.com/portland/stories/2007/01/22/daily45.html |accessdate=December 19, 2012}}</ref> In May 2009, United Streetcar delivered its first prototype to Portland for testing on existing tracks; it was the first U.S.-built streetcar in nearly 60 years.<ref name=\"trib-2009may14\">{{cite news |last=MacKinnon |first=Mary |title=Streetcars soon to be made in Oregon |newspaper=[[Portland Tribune]] |date=May 14, 2009<!--(later re-dated May 13)--> |url=http://portlandtribune.com/component/content/article?id=49492 |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref> That August, the city signed a $20{{nbsp}}million contract to purchase six new streetcars from the manufacturer for the eastside extension.<ref name=\"Oreg14Aug09\">{{cite news |last=Rivera |first=Dylan |title=Portland inks $20 million deal for locally made streetcars |date=August 14, 2009 |newspaper=The Oregonian |url=http://www.oregonlive.com/news/index.ssf/2009/08/portland_inks_20_million_deal.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090817123910/http://www.oregonlive.com/news/index.ssf/2009/08/portland_inks_20_million_deal.html |archivedate=17 August 2009 |url-status=live |accessdate=June 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\nGroundbreaking for the Eastside Streetcar Loop project took place on June 25, 2009. The city selected [[Stacy and Witbeck]] to be the project's general contractor and actual construction began the following year.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.opb.org/news/article/construction-begins-eastside-streetcar-loop/ |last=Baer |first=April |title=Construction Begins On Eastside Streetcar Loop |publisher=[[Oregon Public Broadcasting]] |date=June 25, 2009 |access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref> Across the alignment, crews laid tracks in three- to four-block increments; by February 2010, they were laying tracks on Northeast Grand Avenue.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://djcoregon.com/news/2010/02/09/streetcar-loop-project/ |title=Streetcar Loop Project |last=Carter |first=Dan |publisher=[[Daily Journal of Commerce]] |date=February 9, 2010 |access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref> The Broadway Bridge was closed to all traffic from July 19 to September 3, 2010 to be renovated.<ref>{{cite news |last=Rose |first=Joseph |title=Portland \u2013 Broadway Bridge will close |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=July 18, 2010}}</ref> To maintain the existing weight of the bridge (this was necessary to allow the bridge to continue lifting its spans) and simultaneously add tracks, lighter fiber-reinforced concrete replaced the deck.<ref name=\"streetcar work\">{{cite news|last=Rose|first=Joseph |title=Streetcar work shutting down Broadway Bridge |date=July 5, 2010 <!--(July 4 online edition)--> |newspaper=The Oregonian |page=A10 |url=https://blog.oregonlive.com/commuting/2010/07/streetcar_work_shuts_broadway.html |accessdate=November 9, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"wrap-up-broadway\">{{cite news |url=https://djcoregon.com/news/2011/02/18/streetcar-work-almost-finished-on-broadway-bridge/ |last=Vorenberg |first=Sue |title=Streetcar work wraps up on Broadway Bridge |publisher=Daily Journal of Commerce |date=February 18, 2011 |access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref> In the [[Pearl District, Portland, Oregon|Pearl District]], sections of two former two-way streets\u2014Northwest Lovejoy and Northwest Northrup\u2014were converted into one way streets following the addition of streetcar tracks. Work completed in this section upon the reopening of the Lovejoy ramp on the west end of the Broadway Bridge in November 2010.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://djcoregon.com/news/2010/11/05/pearl-streets-reopen-with-changed-traffic-patterns/ |last=Vorenberg |first=Sue |title=Pearl streets reopen with changed traffic patterns |publisher=Daily Journal of Commerce |date=November 5, 2010 |access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref> In Southeast Portland, crews built a {{convert|425|ft|m|adj=mid|-long}} bridge that led the streetcar to OMSI, the project's eastern terminus.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://djcoregon.com/news/2010/12/22/portland-streetcar-flyover-bridge-near-omsi/ |last=Carter |first=Dan |title=Portland Streetcar flyover bridge near OMSI |publisher=Daily Journal of Commerce |date=December 22, 2010 |access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2011, the city council agreed to contractual changes that reduced the number of streetcars on order from the original six to five.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://djcoregon.com/news/2011/07/20/eastside-streetcar-loop-will-be-delayed-number-of-cars-reduced/ |last=Webber |first=Angela |title=Eastside streetcar loop will be delayed, number of cars reduced |publisher=Daily Journal of Commerce |date=July 20, 2011 |access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref> United Streetcar had depended on [[Czech Republic|Czech]] firm [[\u0160koda]], which built the system's first streetcars, to build the new streetcars' propulsion system but these failed to meet Portland Streetcar's standards. City officials opted instead to source the propulsion system from Wisconsin-based [[Rockwell Automation]], but this was still being developed at the time. Knowing that waiting on Rockwell would cause more delays, city officials pursued [[Austria]]n manufacturer Elin to produce one for the prototype. All of these changes delayed the project and raised the cost of manufacturing.<ref name=\"oreg-2011jul19\">{{cite news |last=Schmidt |first=Brad |title=Portland's $148.3 million eastside streetcar project delayed five months, includes five streetcars instead of six |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=July 19, 2011 |url=http://www.oregonlive.com/portland/index.ssf/2011/07/portlands_1483_million_eastsid.html |accessdate=September 10, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Opening===\n[[File:Barber Block sunlit with streetcar, 2012.jpg|thumb|left|Car 015 in front of the [[Barber Block]] on Southeast Grand Avenue in 2012]] \n\nThe Central Loop Line began service on September 22, 2012, running from Southwest Market Street to the [[Oregon Museum of Science and Industry]] (OMSI) via the [[Pearl District, Portland, Oregon|Pearl District]].<ref name=\"PS-History\">{{cite web|title=Streetcar History |url=http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/node/33 |publisher=Portland Streetcar |accessdate=September 7, 2015 |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203013400/http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/node/33 |archivedate=December 3, 2013 |df= }}</ref> The {{convert|3.35|mi|km|adj=mid|-long}} line cost $148.3 million to construct and opened five months late,<ref>{{cite news |last=Schmidt |first=Brad |date=July 19, 2011 |title=Portland's $148.3 million eastside streetcar project delayed five months, includes five streetcars instead of six |url=http://www.oregonlive.com/portland/index.ssf/2011/07/portlands_1483_million_eastsid.html |newspaper=[[The Oregonian]] |accessdate=September 17, 2015}}</ref> with 18-minute frequencies instead of the planned 15 minutes due to funding cuts by [[TriMet]] and the [[Government of Portland, Oregon|City of Portland]] as well as delays in streetcar delivery from [[United Streetcar]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Rose |first=Joseph |authorlink=Joseph Rose (journalist) |date=September 21, 2012 |title=Portland Streetcar's eastside loop gets off to hobbled start Saturday |url=http://blog.oregonlive.com/commuting/2012/09/portland_streetcars_eastside_l.html |newspaper=The Oregonian |accessdate=September 7, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=October 5, 2012 |title=Portland Streetcar Introduces \u2018Central Loop\u2019 Service |url=http://newsmanager.commpartners.com/aptapt/issues/2012-10-05/3.html |work=Passenger Transport |publisher=[[American Public Transportation Association]] |accessdate=September 8, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn August 30, 2015, a new temporary schedule eliminated the CL Line in favor of the A Loop and B Loop, extended from SW 10th and Market along the NS Line south to SW Moody Avenue & SW Meade Street in the [[South Waterfront, Portland, Oregon|South Waterfront]]. Streetcars began operating across the new [[Tilikum Crossing]] transit bridge on that date, but not carrying passengers across the bridge during a two-week transitional phase which was referred to as \"pre-revenue service\".<ref name=\"PS-Loop\"/> The line was formally re-branded as the Loop Service on September 12, 2015, when the opening of the Tilikum Crossing to the public permitted streetcars to begin carrying passengers on the route section across the bridge.<ref name=\"PS-Loop\"/><ref name=\"PS-History\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Vincent |first=John M. |date=September 8, 2015 |title=Routes, fares change with expanded streetcar service |url=http://portlandtribune.com/pt/9-news/271906-147003-routes-fares-change-with-expanded-streetcar-service |newspaper=[[The Portland Tribune]] |publisher=[[Pamplin Media Group]] |page=A3 |accessdate=August 23, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151128143529/http://portlandtribune.com/pt/9-news/271906-147003-routes-fares-change-with-expanded-streetcar-service |archivedate=November 28, 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n{{clear left}}\n\n==Route==\n[[File:A Lloyd via Peral (21612375879).jpg|thumb|right|An A Loop streetcar on Tilikum Crossing in 2015]]\n[[File:Portland Streetcar car 023 at west end of Broadway Bridge in 2016.jpg|thumb|right|A B Loop streetcar crossing the Broadway Bridge in 2016]]\n\n===Stations===\n\nThe Loop Service serves 52 stations, of which 24 are shared with the NS Line.<ref name=\"maps-schedules\">{{cite web |url=https://portlandstreetcar.org/schedules |title=Maps + Schedules \u2013 Portland Streetcar |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |access-date=March 18, 2019}}</ref> Each platform is equipped with a [[ticket vending machine]], [[passenger information system|real-time display]] system, and line information signs.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://portlandstreetcar.org/ride-guide/how-to-ride |title=Ride Guide |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |access-date=April 1, 2019}}</ref> All stations are [[Accessibility|accessible]] to users with [[Physical disability|limited mobility]].<ref name=\"accessibility-info\">{{cite web |url=http://portlandstreetcar.org/node/8 |title=Accessibility Info |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |access-date=June 6, 2019 |archive-date=February 1, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120201000132/http://portlandstreetcar.org/node/8 |url-status=unfit}}</ref> Connections to MAX Light Rail are available at 10 stops across the line.<ref name=\"Transit Mall map\">{{cite map |url=https://trimet.org/maps/pdf/citycenter.pdf |title=Portland City Center and Transit Mall |publisher=TriMet |access-date=July 30, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190210193921/https://trimet.org/maps/pdf/citycenter.pdf |archive-date=February 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! colspan=2 | Station\n! rowspan=2 | Neighborhood\n! rowspan=2 |Connections and notes<ref name=\"maps-schedules\"/>\n|-\n! A Loop{{br}}(clockwise)\n! B Loop{{br}}(counterclockwise)\n|-\n| \u2014\n| Northwest 10th & Northrup\n| rowspan=\"6\" align=\"center\" | [[Pearl District, Portland, Oregon|Pearl District]]\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}\n|-\n| \u2014\n| Northwest 11th & Marshall\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Northwest 9th & Lovejoy\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Northwest 10th & Johnson\n| Northwest 11th & Johnson\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}\n|-\n| Northwest 10th & Glisan\n| Northwest 11th & Glisan\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}\n|-\n| Northwest 10th & Couch\n| Northwest 11th & Couch\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}{{br}}Serves [[First Regiment Armory Annex|The Armory]], [[Powell's Books|Powell's City of Books]]\n|-\n| Southwest 10th & Alder\n| Southwest 11th & Alder\n| rowspan=\"10\" align=\"center\" | [[Downtown Portland, Oregon|Downtown]]\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}\n|-\n| Central Library\n| Southwest 11th & Taylor\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}; {{rint|light rail|link=MAX Light Rail}} [[Library/Southwest 9th Avenue and Galleria/Southwest 10th Avenue stations|Library and Galleria stations]]: [[MAX Blue Line|Blue]], [[MAX Red Line|Red]] lines{{br}}Serves [[Central Library (Portland, Oregon)|Central Library]]\n|-\n| Art Museum\n| Southwest 11th & Jefferson\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}{{br}}Serves [[Portland Art Museum]]\n|-\n| Southwest 10th & Clay\n| Southwest 11th & Clay\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}\n|-\n| Southwest Park & Mill\n| Southwest Park & Market\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}{{br}}Serves [[South Park Blocks]]\n|-\n| \u2014\n| Southwest 5th & Market\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}{{br}}Serves [[Portland State University]]\n|-\n| PSU Urban Center\n| Southwest 5th & Montgomery\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}; {{rint|light rail|link=MAX Light Rail}} [[PSU Urban Center stations]]: [[MAX Green Line|Green]], [[MAX Orange Line|Orange]], [[MAX Yellow Line|Yellow]] lines{{br}}Serves [[Portland State University]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" | Southwest 3rd & Harrison\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" | Southwest Harrison Street\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}{{br}}Serves [[RiverPlace]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" | Southwest River Parkway & Moody\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}{{br}}Serves [[RiverPlace]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" | Southwest Moody & Meade\n| align=\"center\" | [[South Waterfront]]\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}; {{rint|light rail|link=MAX Light Rail}} [[South Waterfront/Southwest Moody station]]: [[MAX Orange Line|Orange Line]]{{br}}Serves [[Oregon Health and Sciences University|OHSU]] Robertson Life Sciences Building, [[Tilikum Crossing]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" | OMSI\n| rowspan=\"7\" align=\"center\" | [[Central Eastside, Portland, Oregon|Central Eastside]]\n| {{rint|light rail|link=MAX Light Rail}} [[OMSI/Southeast Water station]]: [[MAX Orange Line|Orange Line]]{{br}}Serves [[Oregon Museum of Science and Industry]], [[Tilikum Crossing]]\n|-\n| Southeast MLK & Mill\n| Southeast Grand & Mill\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Southeast MLK & Hawthorne\n| Southeast Grand & Hawthorne\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Southeast MLK & Taylor\n| Southeast Grand & Taylor\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Southeast MLK & Morrison\n| Southeast Grand & Morrison\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Southeast MLK & Stark\n| Southeast Grand & Stark\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Northeast MLK & East Burnside\n| Southeast Grand & East Burnside\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Oregon Convention Center\n| Northeast Grand & Hoyt\n| rowspan=\"7\" align=\"center\" | [[Lloyd District, Portland, Oregon|Lloyd District]]\n| {{rint|light rail|link=MAX Light Rail}} [[Convention Center station (TriMet)|Convention Center station]]: [[MAX Blue Line|Blue]], [[MAX Green Line|Green]], and [[MAX Red Line|Red]] lines{{br}}Serves [[Oregon Convention Center]]\n|-\n| Northeast Oregon & Grand\n| Northeast Grand & Holladay\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Northeast 7th & Holladay\n| Northeast Grand & Multnomah\n| {{rint|light rail|link=MAX Light Rail}} [[Northeast 7th Avenue station]]: [[MAX Blue Line|Blue]], [[MAX Green Line|Green]], and [[MAX Red Line|Red]] lines\n|-\n| Northeast 7th & Halsey\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Northeast Weidler & Grand\n| Northeast Grand & Broadway\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Northeast Weidler & 2nd\n| Northeast Broadway & 2nd\n| \u2014\n|-\n| North Weidler & Ross\n| North Broadway & Ross\n| \u2014\n|}\n\n==Service==\n\nThe Loop Service operates from 5:30&nbsp;a.m. to 11:30&nbsp;p.m. on weekdays, from 7:30&nbsp;a.m. to 11:30&nbsp;p.m. on Saturdays, and from 7:30&nbsp;a.m. to 10:30&nbsp;p.m. on Sundays. Frequencies in each direction range from 15 minutes between 10:00&nbsp;a.m. and 7:00&nbsp;pm on weekdays and Saturdays to 20 minutes on Sundays.<ref name=\"Schedule\">{{cite web |date=August 30, 2015 |title=Streetcar Schedule |url=http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/node/3 |publisher=Portland Streetcar |accessdate=September 29, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Attached KML |display=title,inline}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20150806004043/http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/node/193 Portland Streetcar Loop Service]\n*[http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/node/3 Portland Streetcar schedule]\n\n{{Portland Transit}}\n{{Streetcars Portland Oregon}}\n{{Portal bar|Oregon|Trains|Transport}}\n\n[[Category:2012 establishments in Oregon]]\n[[Category:Passenger rail transportation in Oregon]]\n[[Category:Railway lines opened in 2012]]\n[[Category:Streetcars in Oregon]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Portland, Oregon]]\n[[Category:TriMet]]\n", "name_user": "Truflip99", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFunding and construction:dash", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Loop_Service"}
{"title_page": "MotoE World Cup", "text_new": "{{For|the FIM eRoad Racing World Cup held in 2013|FIM eRoad Racing World Cup}}\n\n{{Infobox motorsport championship\n| name            = MotoE World Cup\n| logo            = Logo_motoe.png\n| image-size      = \n| caption         = \n| category        = [[Motorcycle sport]]\n| country/region  = Europe\n| inaugural       = \n| inaugural2      = [[2019 MotoE season|2019]]\n| folded          = \n| classes         = \n| riders          = 18\n| teams           = 11\n| constructors    = [[Energica Motor Company|Energica]]<ref name=\"Bike\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cycleworld.com/dorna-launches-fim-enel-motoe-world-cup-bike-in-italy|title=Dorna Launches FIM Enel MotoE World Cup Bike In Italy|publisher=cycleworld.com|accessdate=2018-02-07}}</ref>\n| engines         = \n| tyres           = {{Michelin}} [[Michelin]]\n| champion driver = \n| champion rider  = {{flagicon|ITA}} [[Matteo Ferrari (motorcyclist)|Matteo Ferrari]]\n| champion team   =\n| website         = [http://www.motogp.com/en/FIM+Enel+MotoE+World+Cup motogp.com]\n| current_season  = 2019 MotoE season\n}}\n{{MotoGP overview}}\n'''MotoE''', officially the '''FIM [[Enel]] MotoE World Cup''', is a class of [[motorcycle racing]] that uses only [[electric motorcycle]]s. The series is sanctioned by the [[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Motocyclisme|FIM]] and the [[2019 MotoE season|inaugural season]] in 2019 will support [[MotoGP]] at five of the European circuits.<ref name=\"MotoE\">{{cite web|url=http://www.motogp.com/en/news/2018/02/06/fim-enel-motoe-world-cup-a-new-class-of-competition/249159|title=FIM Enel MotoE\u2122 World Cup: a new class of competition|publisher=motogp.com|accessdate=2018-02-07}}</ref> A fire in March 2019 involving recharging batteries destroyed the special facility and the race machines at [[Circuito de Jerez]], Spain. The opening two race events, intended to be at Jerez on 5 May and [[Circuit de la Sarthe|Le Mans]], France on 19 May, were cancelled,<ref name=\"fire cancellation Autosport\">[https://www.autosport.com/motogp/news/142110/motoe-to-go-ahead-despite-canned-opener-fire MotoE 2019 season will go ahead despite cancelled opener] ''[[Autosport]]'', 14 March 2019. Retrieved 2019</ref> with a new schedule announced in late March of six races at four venues starting in July.<ref name=\"revised calendar\">[http://www.motogp.com/en/news/2019/03/26/new-motoe-calendar-announced/287184 New MotoE\u2122 calendar announced], MotoGP.com. Retrieved 29 March 2019</ref>\n\n==Technical specifications==\n\nThe series will be using a spec{{what|date=December 2018}} [[Energica Ego]] Corsa motorcycle, manufactured by [[Energica Motor Company]].<ref name=\"Bike\"/><ref>{{cite web |title=Discover the Energica Ego Corsa MotoE\u2122 motorcycle! |url=http://www.motogp.com/en/news/2018/02/07/discover-the-energica-ego-corsa-motoe-motorcycle/256857 |website=MotoGP |accessdate=5 November 2018}}</ref>\n\t\n* '''Motor''': Synchronous oil-cooled AC with permanent magnets\n* '''Maximum Continuous Power''': 120 kW (160 hp/cv)\n* '''Acceleration''': 0-60 mph in three seconds\n* '''Top Speed''': 270 km/h (168 mph)\n* '''Torque''': 147.5 lb.-ft. (5,000 rpm)\n* '''Frame''': Tubular steel trellis\n* '''Swingarm''': Cast aluminium\n* '''Wheels''': Forged aluminium\n* '''Throttle''': Ride-by-wire\n* '''Battery''': High-voltage lithium-ion\n* '''Recharging''': 0-85 percent in about 20 minutes, via the integrated DC fast charging technology developed by CCS Combo\n\n==Seasons==\n\n===2019===\n{{main|2019 MotoE season}}\n\nThe inaugural season took place over 6 rounds between July and December 2019. The first MotoE champion is Italian rider [[Matteo Ferrari (motorcyclist)|Matteo Ferrari]]. The season start was originally planned for May, but had to be postponed because of a fire at the Jerez test in March where all competition bikes were destroyed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.motorsport.com/motoe/news/motoe-cause-of-fire-disaster/4353463/|title=MotoE reveals cause of Jerez fire disaster|publisher=motorsport.com|date=2019-03-16}}1</ref>\n\n===2020===\n{{main|2020 MotoE season}}\n\nThe second season will be contested over 7 rounds between May and December 2020.\n\n==See also==\n* [[FIM eRoad Racing World Cup]]\n* [[Electric motorsport]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n== External link ==\n* {{Official website| https://www.motogp.com/en/FIM+Enel+MotoE+World+Cup}}\n{{Grand Prix motorcycle racing seasons}}\n\n[[Category:Electric motorcycles]]\n[[Category:Green racing]]\n[[Category:Motorcycle road racing series]]\n[[Category:F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Motocyclisme]]\n[[Category:Recurring sporting events established in 2019]]\n[[Category:World cups]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the FIM eRoad Racing World Cup held in 2013|FIM eRoad Racing World Cup}}\n\n{{Infobox motorsport championship\n| name            = MotoE World Cup\n| logo            = Logo_motoe.png\n| image-size      = \n| caption         = \n| category        = [[Motorcycle sport]]\n| country/region  = Europe\n| inaugural       = \n| inaugural2      = [[2019 MotoE season|2019]]\n| folded          = \n| classes         = \n| riders          = 18\n| teams           = 11\n| constructors    = [[Energica Motor Company|Energica]]<ref name=\"Bike\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cycleworld.com/dorna-launches-fim-enel-motoe-world-cup-bike-in-italy|title=Dorna Launches FIM Enel MotoE World Cup Bike In Italy|publisher=cycleworld.com|accessdate=2018-02-07}}</ref>\n| engines         = \n| tyres           = {{Michelin}} [[Michelin]]\n| champion driver = \n| champion rider  = {{flagicon|ITA}} [[Matteo Ferrari (motorcyclist)|Matteo Ferrari]]\n| champion team   =\n| website         = [http://www.motogp.com/en/FIM+Enel+MotoE+World+Cup motogp.com]\n| current_season  = 2019 MotoE season\n}}\n{{MotoGP overview}}\n'''MotoE''', officially the '''FIM [[Enel]] MotoE World Cup''', is a class of [[motorcycle racing]] that uses only [[electric motorcycle]]s. The series is sanctioned by the [[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Motocyclisme|FIM]] and the [[2019 MotoE season|inaugural season]] in 2019 will support [[MotoGP]] at five of the European circuits.<ref name=\"MotoE\">{{cite web|url=http://www.motogp.com/en/news/2018/02/06/fim-enel-motoe-world-cup-a-new-class-of-competition/249159|title=FIM Enel MotoE\u2122 World Cup: a new class of competition|publisher=motogp.com|accessdate=2018-02-07}}</ref> A fire in March 2019 involving recharging batteries destroyed the special facility and the race machines at [[Circuito de Jerez]], Spain. The opening two race events, intended to be at Jerez on 5 May and [[Circuit de la Sarthe|Le Mans]], France on 19 May, were cancelled,<ref name=\"fire cancellation Autosport\">[https://www.autosport.com/motogp/news/142110/motoe-to-go-ahead-despite-canned-opener-fire MotoE 2019 season will go ahead despite cancelled opener] ''[[Autosport]]'', 14 March 2019. Retrieved 2019</ref> with a new schedule announced in late March of six races at four venues starting in July.<ref name=\"revised calendar\">[http://www.motogp.com/en/news/2019/03/26/new-motoe-calendar-announced/287184 New MotoE\u2122 calendar announced], MotoGP.com. Retrieved 29 March 2019</ref>\n\n==Technical specifications==\n\nThe series will be using a spec{{what|date=December 2018}} [[Energica Ego]] Corsa motorcycle, manufactured by [[Energica Motor Company]].<ref name=\"Bike\"/><ref>{{cite web |title=Discover the Energica Ego Corsa MotoE\u2122 motorcycle! |url=http://www.motogp.com/en/news/2018/02/07/discover-the-energica-ego-corsa-motoe-motorcycle/256857 |website=MotoGP |accessdate=5 November 2018}}</ref>\n\t\n* '''Motor''': Synchronous oil-cooled AC with permanent magnets\n* '''Maximum Continuous Power''': 120 kW (160 hp/cv)\n* '''Acceleration''': 0-60 mph in three seconds\n* '''Top Speed''': 270 km/h (168 mph)\n* '''Torque''': 147.5 lb.-ft. (5,000 rpm)\n* '''Frame''': Tubular steel trellis\n* '''Swingarm''': Cast aluminium\n* '''Wheels''': Forged aluminium\n* '''Throttle''': Ride-by-wire\n* '''Battery''': High-voltage lithium-ion\n* '''Recharging''': 0-85 percent in about 20 minutes, via the integrated DC fast charging technology developed by CCS Combo\n\n==Seasons==\n\n===2019===\n{{main|2019 MotoE season}}\n\nThe inaugural season took place over 6 rounds between July and December 2019. The first MotoE champion is Italian rider [[Matteo Ferrari]]. The season start was originally planned for May, but had to be postponed because of a fire at the Jerez test in March where all competition bikes were destroyed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.motorsport.com/motoe/news/motoe-cause-of-fire-disaster/4353463/|title=MotoE reveals cause of Jerez fire disaster|publisher=motorsport.com|date=2019-03-16}}1</ref>\n\n===2020===\n{{main|2020 MotoE season}}\n\nThe second season will be contested over 7 rounds between May and December 2020.\n\n==See also==\n* [[FIM eRoad Racing World Cup]]\n* [[Electric motorsport]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n== External link ==\n* {{Official website| https://www.motogp.com/en/FIM+Enel+MotoE+World+Cup}}\n{{Grand Prix motorcycle racing seasons}}\n\n[[Category:Electric motorcycles]]\n[[Category:Green racing]]\n[[Category:Motorcycle road racing series]]\n[[Category:F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Motocyclisme]]\n[[Category:Recurring sporting events established in 2019]]\n[[Category:World cups]]\n", "name_user": "Sausius", "label": "safe", "comment": "Changed the reference for Matteo Ferrari to the correct Matteo Ferrari (the motorcyclist, not the soccer player).", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MotoE_World_Cup"}
{"title_page": "Kobi, Georgia", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name = Kobi\n| native_name             = {{lang-ka|\u10d9\u10dd\u10d1\u10d8}}\n|image_skyline        = Village Kobi.jpg\n|imagesize            = 250px\n|pushpin_map          = Georgia (country)#Georgia Mtskheta-Mtianeti\n|mapsize              = 280px\n|map_caption          = Location of Kobi in Georgia\n|subdivision_type     = [[Countries of the world|Country]]\n|subdivision_name     = {{GEO}}\n|subdivision_type1      = [[Mkhare]]\n|subdivision_name1      = [[Mtskheta-Mtianeti]]\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Municipality]]\n|subdivision_name2      = [[Kazbegi Municipality|Kazbegi]]\n|area_magnitude       = \n|area_total_km2           = \n|area_land_km2            = \n|area_water_km2           = \n|population_as_of     = 2014\n|population_footnotes = <ref>{{Georgian census 2014}}</ref>\n|population_total     = 3\n|population_density_km2   = \n|timezone             = Georgian Time\n|utc_offset           = +4\n|timezone_DST         = <!-- No DST in Georgia since 2005 -->\n|utc_offset_DST       = \n|coordinates          = {{coord|42|33|34|N|44|30|43|E|region:GE_type:city|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation_m            = 1970\n|website              = \n|footnotes            = \n}}\n'''Kobi''' ({{lang-ka|\u10d9\u10dd\u10d1\u10d8}}, {{lang-os|\u041a\u044a\u043e\u0431}}) is a village in the historical region of [[Khevi]], [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]]. Administratively, it is part of the [[Kazbegi Municipality]] in [[Mtskheta-Mtianeti]]. It is a community center of Truso Valley villages. Distance to the municipality center [[Stepantsminda]] is 20 km.\n==Transportation ==\nVillage is located on [[Georgian Military Road]].\n\n== Climate ==\n{{Weather box\n| width = auto\n| open = yes\n| single line = yes\n| metric first = yes\n| location = Kobi \n| precipitation colour = green\n| Jan mean C = -7.1\n| Feb mean C = -6.9\n| Mar mean C = -2.9\n| Apr mean C = 2\n| May mean C = 7.1\n| Jun mean C = 10.2\n| J